**Clinical Reasoning:**
Th1 cells play a crucial role in combating mycobacterial infections like tuberculosis by secreting interferon-gamma (IFN-γ), which activates macrophages to enhance phagosome-lysosome fusion and nitric oxide (NO) production—the key mechanism for killing intracellular M. tuberculosis. While some evidence references tuberculin tests and pulmonary inflammation patterns suggestive of TB exposure, none directly state that IL-4, TNF-alpha, or histamine mediate macrophage activation via phagosomal fusion or NO release. Only IFN-γ has well-established roles in activating macrophages through these pathways.

